[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] In computability theory, the **Ackermann function**, named after Wilhelm Ackermann, is one of the simplest and earliest-discovered examples of a total computable function that is not primitive recursive.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] All primitive recursive functions are total and computable, but the Ackermann function illustrates that not all total computable functions are primitive recursive.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] It is essentially constructed by diagonalizing a sequence of primitive recursive functions $f_{1},f_{2},\dots$ selected from the Grzegorczyk hierarchy.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] This makes the Ackermann function the first limit point $f_{\omega }$ of the fast-growing hierarchy.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] After Ackermann's publication of his function (which had three non-negative integer arguments), many authors modified it to suit various purposes, so that today "the Ackermann function" may refer to any of numerous variants of the original function.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] One common version is the two-argument **Ackermann–Péter function** developed by Rózsa Péter and Raphael Robinson.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] This function is defined from the recurrence relation $\operatorname {A} (m+1,n+1)=\operatorname {A} (m,\operatorname {A} (m+1,n))$ with appropriate base cases.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Its value grows very rapidly; for example, $\operatorname {A} (4,2)$ results in $2^{65536}-3$ , an integer with 19,729 decimal digits.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] In the late 1920s, the mathematicians Gabriel Sudan and Wilhelm Ackermann, students of David Hilbert, were studying the foundations of computation.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Both Sudan and Ackermann are credited with discovering total computable functions (termed simply "recursive" in some references) that are not primitive recursive.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Sudan published the lesser-known Sudan function, then shortly afterwards and independently, in 1928, Ackermann published his function $\varphi$ (from Greek, the letter *phi*).
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] In *On the Infinite*, David Hilbert first hypothesized that the Ackermann function was not primitive recursive, but it was Ackermann, Hilbert's personal secretary and former student, who actually proved the hypothesis in his paper *On Hilbert's Construction of the Real Numbers*.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Rózsa Péter and Raphael Robinson later developed a two-variable version of the Ackermann function that became preferred by almost all authors.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The generalized hyperoperation sequence, e.g. $G(m,a,b)=a[m]b$ , is a version of the Ackermann function as well.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Many other versions of Ackermann function have been investigated.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] By induction on m , one can show that $F(m,n)\leq A(m,n)$ for all $m,n\in \mathbb {N} _{0}$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Iteration is the process of composing a function with itself a certain number of times.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Function composition is an associative operation, so $f(f^{n}(x))=f^{n}(f(x))$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Conceiving the Ackermann function as a sequence of unary functions, one can set $\operatorname {A} _{m}(n)=\operatorname {A} (m,n)$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The function $\operatorname {A} _{k}(n)$ can also be computed by a LOOP-k program.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] It is obvious that $\operatorname {A} (m,n)$ , not being a primitive recursive function —see below—, cannot be computed by a LOOP program.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The recursive definition of the Ackermann function can naturally be transposed to a term rewriting system (TRS).
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] To compute $\operatorname {A} (m,n)$ one can use a stack, which initially contains the elements $\langle m,n\rangle$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The pseudocode is published in Grossman & Zeitman (1988).
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Like in the previous section the computation of $\operatorname {A} _{m}^{1}(n)$ can be implemented with a stack.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Initially the stack contains the three elements $\langle 1,m,n\rangle$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] These rules take care of the base case $A(0,n)$ , the alignment $(n+3)$ and the fudge (-3).
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Computing the Ackermann function can be restated in terms of an infinite table.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] First, place the natural numbers along the top row.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] To determine a number in the table, take the number immediately to the left.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Then use that number to look up the required number in the column given by that number and one row up.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] If there is no number to its left, simply look at the column headed "1" in the previous row.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The numbers here that are only expressed with recursive exponentiation or Knuth arrows are very large and would take up too much space to notate in plain decimal digits.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Despite the large values occurring in this early section of the table, some even larger numbers have been defined, such as Graham's number, which cannot be written with any small number of Knuth arrows.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] This number is constructed with a technique similar to applying the Ackermann function to itself recursively.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The Ackermann function grows faster than any primitive recursive function and therefore is not itself primitive recursive.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Primitive recursive functions are built from basic functions using composition and primitive recursion, and all grow within a certain rate.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] where $\operatorname {FGH} _{k}^{n}$ denotes n -fold iteration of $\operatorname {FGH} _{k}$ on input n .
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] This hierarchy grows strictly faster with increasing k , and every primitive recursive function is eventually bounded above by some $\operatorname {FGH} _{k}$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] This can be shown by structural induction on the definitions of primitive recursive functions.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] However, the Ackermann function $\operatorname {A} (m,n)$ eventually exceeds every $\operatorname {FGH} _{k}$ ; for every k , there exists m such that $\operatorname {A} (m,n)>\operatorname {FGH} _{k}(n)$ for all sufficiently large n .
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Thus, $\operatorname {A}$ grows faster than any primitive recursive function and is therefore not primitive recursive.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Since the function *f*(*n*) = *A*(*n*, *n*) considered above grows very rapidly, its inverse function, *f*−1, grows very slowly.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] This **inverse Ackermann function** *f*−1 is usually denoted by ***α***.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] This inverse appears in the time complexity of some algorithms, such as the disjoint-set data structure and Chazelle's algorithm for minimum spanning trees.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Sometimes Ackermann's original function or other variations are used in these settings, but they all grow at similarly high rates.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] In particular, some modified functions simplify the expression by eliminating the −3 and similar terms.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] This function arises in more precise analyses of the algorithms mentioned above, and gives a more refined time bound.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] In the disjoint-set data structure, *m* represents the number of operations while *n* represents the number of elements; in the minimum spanning tree algorithm, *m* represents the number of edges while *n* represents the number of vertices.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Several slightly different definitions of *α*(*m*, *n*) exist; for example, log2 *n* is sometimes replaced by *n*, and the floor function is sometimes replaced by a ceiling.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Other studies might define an inverse function of one where *m* is set to a constant, such that the inverse applies to a particular row.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The inverse of the Ackermann function is primitive recursive, since it is graph primitive recursive, and it is upper bounded by a primitive recursive function.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The Ackermann function appears in the time complexity of some algorithms, such as vector addition systems and Petri net reachability, thus showing they are computationally infeasible for large instances.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The inverse of the Ackermann function appears in some time complexity results.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] For instance, the disjoint-set data structure takes amortized time per operation proportional to the inverse Ackermann function, and cannot be made faster within the cell-probe model of computational complexity.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Certain problems in discrete geometry related to Davenport–Schinzel sequences have complexity bounds in which the inverse Ackermann function $\alpha (n)$ appears.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] For instance, for n line segments in the plane, the unbounded face of the arrangement of the segments has complexity $O(n\alpha (n))$ , and some systems of n line segments have an unbounded face of complexity $\Omega (n\alpha (n))$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The Ackermann function, due to its definition in terms of extremely deep recursion, can be used as a benchmark of a compiler's ability to optimize recursion.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] The first published use of Ackermann's function in this way was in 1970 by Dragoș Vaida and, almost simultaneously, in 1971, by Yngve Sundblad.
[src:union-find-algorithm/ackermann-function] Sundblad's seminal paper was taken up by Brian Wichmann (co-author of the Whetstone benchmark) in a trilogy of papers written between 1975 and 1982.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] In computer science, **amortized analysis** is a method for analyzing a given algorithm's complexity, or how much of a resource, especially time or memory, it takes to execute.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] The motivation for amortized analysis is that looking at the worst-case run time can be too pessimistic.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] Instead, amortized analysis averages the running times of operations in a sequence over that sequence.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] For a given operation of an algorithm, certain situations (e.g., input parametrizations or data structure contents) may imply a significant cost in resources, whereas other situations may not be as costly.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] The amortized analysis considers both the costly and less costly operations together over the whole sequence of operations.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] This may include accounting for different types of input, length of the input, and other factors that affect its performance.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis initially emerged from a method called aggregate analysis, which is now subsumed by amortized analysis.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] The technique was first formally introduced by Robert Tarjan in his 1985 paper *Amortized Computational Complexity*, which addressed the need for a more useful form of analysis than the common probabilistic methods used.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] Amortization was initially used for very specific types of algorithms, particularly those involving binary trees and union operations.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] However, it is now ubiquitous and comes into play when analyzing many other algorithms as well.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis requires knowledge of which series of operations are possible.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] This is most commonly the case with data structures, which have a state that persists between operations.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] The basic idea is that a worst-case operation can alter the state in such a way that the worst case cannot occur again for a long time, thus "amortizing" its cost.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] There are generally three methods for performing amortized analysis: the aggregate method, the accounting method, and the potential method.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] All of these give correct answers; the choice of which to use depends on which is most convenient for a particular situation.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] Consider a dynamic array that grows in size as more elements are added to it, such as `ArrayList` in Java or `std::vector` in C++.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] If we started out with a dynamic array of size 4, we could push 4 elements onto it, and each operation would take constant time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] Yet pushing a fifth element onto that array would take longer as the array would have to create a new array of a scaled size, copy the old elements onto the new array, then add the new element.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] The next few push operations would similarly take constant time, then the subsequent addition would require another slow scaling of the array size.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] In general, for an arbitrary number n of pushes to an array of any initial size, the times for steps that scale the array add in a geometric series to $O(n)$ , while the constant times for each remaining push also add to $O(n)$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] Therefore the average time per push operation is $O(n)/n=O(1)$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] This reasoning can be formalized and generalized to more complicated data structures using amortized analysis.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] The enqueue operation just pushes an element onto the input array; this operation does not depend on the lengths of either input or output and therefore runs in constant time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] However the dequeue operation is more complicated.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] If the output array already has some elements in it, then dequeue runs in constant time; otherwise, dequeue takes ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time to add all the elements onto the output array from the input array, where *n* is the current length of the input array.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] After copying *n* elements from input, we can perform *n* dequeue operations, each taking constant time, before the output array is empty again.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] Thus, we can perform a sequence of *n* dequeue operations in only ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, which implies that the amortized time of each dequeue operation is ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] Alternatively, we can charge the cost of copying any item from the input array to the output array to the earlier enqueue operation for that item.
[src:union-find-algorithm/amortized-analysis] This charging scheme doubles the amortized time for enqueue but reduces the amortized time for dequeue to ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **component** of an undirected graph is a connected subgraph that is not part of any larger connected subgraph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The components of any graph partition its vertices into disjoint sets, and are the induced subgraphs of those sets.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] A graph that is itself connected has exactly one component, consisting of the whole graph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Components are sometimes called **connected components**.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The number of components in a given graph is an important graph invariant, and is closely related to invariants of matroids, topological spaces, and matrices.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In random graphs, a frequently occurring phenomenon is the incidence of a giant component, one component that is significantly larger than the others; and of a percolation threshold, an edge probability above which a giant component exists and below which it does not.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The components of a graph can be constructed in linear time, and a special case of the problem, connected-component labeling, is a basic technique in image analysis.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Dynamic connectivity algorithms maintain components as edges are inserted or deleted in a graph, in low time per change.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In computational complexity theory, connected components have been used to study algorithms with limited space complexity, and sublinear time algorithms can accurately estimate the number of components.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] A component of a given undirected graph may be defined as a connected subgraph that is not part of any larger connected subgraph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] For instance, the graph shown in the first illustration has three components.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Every vertex v of a graph belongs to one of the graph's components, which may be found as the induced subgraph of the set of vertices reachable from v .
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Every graph is the disjoint union of its components.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Another definition of components involves the equivalence classes of an equivalence relation defined on the graph's vertices.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In an undirected graph, a vertex v is *reachable* from a vertex u if there is a path from u to v , or equivalently a walk (a path allowing repeated vertices and edges).
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The equivalence classes of this relation partition the vertices of the graph into disjoint sets, subsets of vertices that are all reachable from each other, with no additional reachable pairs outside of any of these subsets.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Each vertex belongs to exactly one equivalence class.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The components are then the induced subgraphs formed by each of these equivalence classes.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Alternatively, some sources define components as the sets of vertices rather than as the subgraphs they induce.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Similar definitions involving equivalence classes have been used to defined components for other forms of graph connectivity, including the weak components and strongly connected components of directed graphs and the biconnected components of undirected graphs.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The number of components of a given finite graph can be used to count the number of edges in its spanning forests: In a graph with n vertices and c components, every spanning forest will have exactly $n-c$ edges.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] This number $n-c$ is the matroid-theoretic rank of the graph, and the rank of its graphic matroid.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The rank of the dual cographic matroid equals the circuit rank of the graph, the minimum number of edges that must be removed from the graph to break all its cycles.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In a graph with m edges, n vertices and c components, the circuit rank is $m-n+c$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] A graph can be interpreted as a topological space in multiple ways, for instance by placing its vertices as points in general position in three-dimensional Euclidean space and representing its edges as line segments between those points.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The components of a graph can be generalized through these interpretations as the topological connected components of the corresponding space; these are equivalence classes of points that cannot be separated by pairs of disjoint closed sets.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Just as the number of connected components of a topological space is an important topological invariant, the zeroth Betti number, the number of components of a graph is an important graph invariant, and in topological graph theory it can be interpreted as the zeroth Betti number of the graph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The number of components arises in other ways in graph theory as well.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In algebraic graph theory it equals the multiplicity of 0 as an eigenvalue of the Laplacian matrix of a finite graph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] It is also the index of the first nonzero coefficient of the chromatic polynomial of the graph, and the chromatic polynomial of the whole graph can be obtained as the product of the polynomials of its components.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Numbers of components play a key role in Tutte's theorem on perfect matchings characterizing finite graphs that have perfect matchings and the associated Tutte–Berge formula for the size of a maximum matching, and in the definition of graph toughness.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] It is straightforward to compute the components of a finite graph in linear time (in terms of the numbers of the vertices and edges of the graph) using either breadth-first search or depth-first search.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In either case, a search that begins at some particular vertex v will find the entire component containing v (and no more) before returning.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] All components of a graph can be found by looping through its vertices, starting a new breadth-first or depth-first search whenever the loop reaches a vertex that has not already been included in a previously found component.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Hopcroft & Tarjan (1973) describe essentially this algorithm, and state that it was already "well known".
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Connected-component labeling, a basic technique in computer image analysis, involves the construction of a graph from the image and component analysis on the graph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The vertices are the subset of the pixels of the image, chosen as being of interest or as likely to be part of depicted objects.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Edges connect adjacent pixels, with adjacency defined either orthogonally according to the Von Neumann neighborhood, or both orthogonally and diagonally according to the Moore neighborhood.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Identifying the connected components of this graph allows additional processing to find more structure in those parts of the image or identify what kind of object is depicted.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Researchers have developed component-finding algorithms specialized for this type of graph, allowing it to be processed in pixel order rather than in the more scattered order that would be generated by breadth-first or depth-first searching.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] This can be useful in situations where sequential access to the pixels is more efficient than random access, either because the image is represented in a hierarchical way that does not permit fast random access or because sequential access produces better memory access patterns.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] These algorithms take amortized time $O(\alpha (n))$ per operation, where adding vertices and edges and determining the component in which a vertex falls are both operations, and $\alpha$ is a very slowly growing inverse of the very quickly growing Ackermann function.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] When both edge insertions and edge deletions are allowed, dynamic connectivity algorithms can still maintain the same information, in amortized time $O(\log ^{2}n/\log \log n)$ per change and time $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ per connectivity query, or in near-logarithmic randomized expected time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Components of graphs have been used in computational complexity theory to study the power of Turing machines that have a working memory limited to a logarithmic number of bits, with the much larger input accessible only through read access rather than being modifiable.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The problems that can be solved by machines limited in this way define the complexity class L.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] It was finally proven in 2008 that this connectivity problem can be solved in logarithmic space, and therefore that SL = L.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In a graph represented as an adjacency list, with random access to its vertices, it is possible to estimate the number of connected components, with constant probability of obtaining additive (absolute) error at most $\varepsilon n$ , in sublinear time $O(\varepsilon ^{-2}\log \varepsilon ^{-1})$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In random graphs the sizes of components are given by a random variable, which, in turn, depends on the specific model of how random graphs are chosen.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The connectivity of this model depends on p , and there are three different ranges of p with very different behavior from each other.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In the analysis below, all outcomes occur with high probability, meaning that the probability of the outcome is arbitrarily close to one for sufficiently large values of n .
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The analysis depends on a parameter $\varepsilon$ , a positive constant independent of n that can be arbitrarily close to zero.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] , all components are simple and very small.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The largest component has logarithmic size.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Most of its components are trees: the number of vertices in components that have cycles grows more slowly than any unbounded function of the number of vertices.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] Every tree of fixed size occurs linearly many times.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] The remaining components are small, with logarithmic size.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] In the same model of random graphs, there will exist multiple connected components with high probability for values of p below a significantly higher threshold, $p<(1-\varepsilon )(\log n)/n$ , and a single connected component for values above the threshold, $p>(1+\varepsilon )(\log n)/n$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] This phenomenon is closely related to the coupon collector's problem: in order to be connected, a random graph needs enough edges for each vertex to be incident to at least one edge.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] More precisely, if random edges are added one by one to a graph, then with high probability the first edge whose addition connects the whole graph touches the last isolated vertex.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] For different models including the random subgraphs of grid graphs, the connected components are described by percolation theory.
[src:union-find-algorithm/connected-component-graph-theory] A key question in this theory is the existence of a percolation threshold, a critical probability above which a giant component (or infinite component) exists and below which it does not.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In computer science, a **disjoint-set data structure**, also called a **union–find data structure** or **merge–find set**, is a data structure that stores a collection of disjoint (non-overlapping) sets.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Equivalently, it stores a partition of a set into disjoint subsets.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] It provides operations for adding new sets, merging sets (replacing them with their union), and finding a representative member of a set.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The last operation makes it possible to determine efficiently whether any two elements belong to the same set or to different sets.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] While there are several ways of implementing disjoint-set data structures, in practice they are often identified with a particular implementation known as a **disjoint-set forest**.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This specialized type of forest performs union and find operations in near-constant amortized time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] For a sequence of m addition, union, or find operations on a disjoint-set forest with n nodes, the total time required is *O*(*m*α(*n*)), where α(*n*) is the extremely slow-growing inverse Ackermann function.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Although disjoint-set forests do not guarantee this time per operation, each operation rebalances the structure (via tree compression) so that subsequent operations become faster.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] As a result, disjoint-set forests are both asymptotically optimal and practically efficient.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set data structures play a key role in Kruskal's algorithm for finding the minimum spanning tree of a graph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The importance of minimum spanning trees means that disjoint-set data structures support a wide variety of algorithms.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In addition, these data structures find applications in symbolic computation and in compilers, especially for register allocation problems.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set forests were first described by Bernard A.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1973, their time complexity was bounded to $O(\log ^{*}(n))$ , the iterated logarithm of n , by Hopcroft and Ullman.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1975, Robert Tarjan was the first to prove the $O(m\alpha (n))$ (inverse Ackermann function) upper bound on the algorithm's time complexity.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1979, he showed that this was the lower bound for a certain class of algorithms, pointer algorithms, that include the Galler-Fischer structure.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1989, Fredman and Saks showed that $\Omega (\alpha (n))$ (amortized) words of $O(\log n)$ bits must be accessed by *any* disjoint-set data structure per operation, thereby proving the optimality of the data structure in this model.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1991, Galil and Italiano published a survey of data structures for disjoint-sets.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Anderson and Heather Woll described a parallelized version of Union–Find that never needs to block.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 2007, Sylvain Conchon and Jean-Christophe Filliâtre developed a semi-persistent version of the disjoint-set forest data structure and formalized its correctness using the proof assistant Rocq (then: *Coq*).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] "Semi-persistent" means that previous versions of the structure are efficiently retained, but accessing previous versions of the data structure invalidates later ones.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Their fastest implementation achieves performance almost as efficient as the non-persistent algorithm.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] They do not perform a complexity analysis.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Variants of disjoint-set data structures with better performance on a restricted class of problems have also been considered.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Gabow and Tarjan showed that if the possible unions are restricted in certain ways, then a truly linear time algorithm is possible.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In particular, linear time is achievable if a "union tree" is given a priori.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This is a tree that includes all elements of the sets.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Let p[*v*] denote the parent in the tree, then the assumption is that union operations must have the form **union**(*v*,p[*v*]) for some *v*.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this and the following section we describe the most common implementation of the disjoint-set data structure, as a forest of parent pointer trees.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This representation is known as **Galler-Fischer trees**.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Each node in a disjoint-set forest consists of a pointer and some auxiliary information, either a size or a rank (but not both).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The pointers are used to make parent pointer trees, where each node that is not the root of a tree points to its parent.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] To distinguish root nodes from others, their parent pointers have invalid values, such as a circular reference to the node or a sentinel value.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Each tree represents a set stored in the forest, with the members of the set being the nodes in the tree.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Root nodes provide set representatives: Two nodes are in the same set if and only if the roots of the trees containing the nodes are equal.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Nodes in the forest can be stored in any way convenient to the application, but a common technique is to store them in an array.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this case, parents can be indicated by their array index.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Every array entry requires Θ(log *n*) bits of storage for the parent pointer.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] A comparable or lesser amount of storage is required for the rest of the entry, so the number of bits required to store the forest is Θ(*n* log *n*).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] If an implementation uses fixed size nodes (thereby limiting the maximum size of the forest that can be stored), then the necessary storage is linear in n.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set data structures support three operations: Making a new set containing a new element; Finding the representative of the set containing a given element; and Merging two sets.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The `MakeSet` operation adds a new element into a new set containing only the new element, and the new set is added to the data structure.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the data structure is instead viewed as a partition of a set, then the `MakeSet` operation enlarges the set by adding the new element, and it extends the existing partition by putting the new element into a new subset containing only the new element.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In a disjoint-set forest, `MakeSet` initializes the node's parent pointer and the node's size or rank.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This operation has linear time complexity.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In particular, initializing a disjoint-set forest with n nodes requires *O*(*n*) time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Lack of a parent assigned to the node implies that the node is not present in the forest.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In practice, `MakeSet` must be preceded by an operation that allocates memory to hold x.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] As long as memory allocation is an amortized constant-time operation, as it is for a good dynamic array implementation, it does not change the asymptotic performance of the random-set forest.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The `Find` operation follows the chain of parent pointers from a specified query node x until it reaches a root element.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This root element represents the set to which x belongs and may be x itself.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] `Find` returns the root element it reaches.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Performing a `Find` operation presents an important opportunity for improving the forest.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The time in a `Find` operation is spent chasing parent pointers, so a flatter tree leads to faster `Find` operations.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] When a `Find` is executed, there is no faster way to reach the root than by following each parent pointer in succession.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] However, the parent pointers visited during this search can be updated to point closer to the root.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Because every element visited on the way to a root is part of the same set, this does not change the sets stored in the forest.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] But it makes future `Find` operations faster, not only for the nodes between the query node and the root, but also for their descendants.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This updating is an important part of the disjoint-set forest's amortized performance guarantee.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] There are several algorithms for `Find` that achieve the asymptotically optimal time complexity.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] One family of algorithms, known as **path compression**, makes every node between the query node and the root point to the root.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This implementation makes two passes, one up the tree and one back down.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] It requires enough scratch memory to store the path from the query node to the root (in the above pseudocode, the path is implicitly represented using the call stack).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This can be decreased to a constant amount of memory by performing both passes in the same direction.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Tarjan and Van Leeuwen also developed one-pass `Find` algorithms that retain the same worst-case complexity but are more efficient in practice.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] These are called path splitting and path halving.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Both of these update the parent pointers of nodes on the path between the query node and the root.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The operation `Union(*x*, *y*)` replaces the set containing x and the set containing y with their union.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] `Union` first uses `Find` to determine the roots of the trees containing x and y.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the roots are the same, there is nothing more to do.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Otherwise, the two trees must be merged.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This is done by either setting the parent pointer of x's root to y's, or setting the parent pointer of y's root to x's.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The choice of which node becomes the parent has consequences for the complexity of future operations on the tree.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] If it is done carelessly, trees can become excessively tall.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] For example, suppose that `Union` always made the tree containing x a subtree of the tree containing y.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The resulting forest contains a single tree whose root is n, and the path from 1 to n passes through every node in the tree.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] For this forest, the time to run `Find(1)` is *O*(*n*).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In an efficient implementation, tree height is controlled using **union by size** or **union by rank**.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Both of these require a node to store information besides just its parent pointer.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This information is used to decide which root becomes the new parent.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Both strategies ensure that trees do not become too deep.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In the case of union by size, a node stores its size, which is simply its number of descendants (including the node itself).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] When the trees with roots x and y are merged, the node with more descendants becomes the parent.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the two nodes have the same number of descendants, then either one can become the parent.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In both cases, the size of the new parent node is set to its new total number of descendants.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The number of bits necessary to store the size is clearly the number of bits necessary to store n.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This adds a constant factor to the forest's required storage.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] For union by rank, a node stores its *rank*, which is an upper bound for its height.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] When a node is initialized, its rank is set to zero.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] To merge trees with roots x and y, first compare their ranks.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the ranks are different, then the larger rank tree becomes the parent, and the ranks of x and y do not change.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the ranks are the same, then either one can become the parent, but the new parent's rank is incremented by one.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] While the rank of a node is clearly related to its height, storing ranks is more efficient than storing heights.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The height of a node can change during a `Find` operation, so storing ranks avoids the extra effort of keeping the height correct.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] It can be shown that every node has rank $\lfloor \log n\rfloor$ or less.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Consequently, each rank can be stored in *O*(log log *n*) bits and all the ranks can be stored in *O*(*n* log log *n*) bits.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This makes the ranks an asymptotically negligible portion of the forest's size.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is clear from the above implementations that the size and rank of a node do not matter unless a node is the root of a tree.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Once a node becomes a child, its size and rank are never accessed again.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] There is a variant of the `Union` operation in which the user determines the representative of the formed set.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is not hard to add this functionality to the above algorithms without losing efficiency.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] A disjoint-set forest implementation in which `Find` does not update parent pointers, and in which `Union` does not attempt to control tree heights, can have trees with height *O*(*n*).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In such a situation, the `Find` and `Union` operations require *O*(*n*) time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] If an implementation uses path compression alone, then a sequence of n `MakeSet` operations, followed by up to *n* − 1 `Union` operations and *f* `Find` operations, has a worst-case running time of $\Theta (n+f\cdot \left(1+\log _{2+f/n}n\right))$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Using union by rank, but without updating parent pointers during `Find`, gives a running time of $\Theta (m\log n)$ for m operations of any type, up to n of which are `MakeSet` operations.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The combination of path compression, splitting, or halving, with union by size or by rank, reduces the running time for m operations of any type, up to n of which are `MakeSet` operations, to $\Theta (m\alpha (n))$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This makes the amortized running time of each operation $\Theta (\alpha (n))$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This is asymptotically optimal, meaning that every disjoint set data structure must use $\Omega (\alpha (n))$ amortized time per operation.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Here, the function $\alpha (n)$ is the inverse Ackermann function.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The inverse Ackermann function grows extraordinarily slowly, so this factor is 4 or less for any n that can actually be written in the physical universe.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This makes disjoint-set operations practically amortized constant time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The precise analysis of the performance of a disjoint-set forest is somewhat intricate.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] However, there is a much simpler analysis that proves that the amortized time for any m `Find` or `Union` operations on a disjoint-set forest containing n objects is *O*(*m* log* *n*), where log* denotes the iterated logarithm.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Lemma 1: As the find function follows the path along to the root, the rank of node it encounters is increasing.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] We claim that as Find and Union operations are applied to the data set, this fact remains true over time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Initially when each node is the root of its own tree, it's trivially true.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The only case when the rank of a node might be changed is when the Union by Rank operation is applied.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this case, a tree with smaller rank will be attached to a tree with greater rank, rather than vice versa.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] And during the find operation, all nodes visited along the path will be attached to the root, which has larger rank than its children, so this operation won't change this fact either.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Lemma 2: A node u which is root of a subtree with rank r has at least $2^{r}$ nodes.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Assume that a node u with rank r has at least 2*r* nodes.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Then when two trees with rank r are merged using the operation Union by Rank, a tree with rank *r* + 1 results, the root of which has at least $2^{r}+2^{r}=2^{r+1}$ nodes.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] From lemma 2, we know that a node u which is root of a subtree with rank r has at least $2^{r}$ nodes.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] We will get the maximum number of nodes of rank r when each node with rank r is the root of a tree that has exactly $2^{r}$ nodes.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] At any particular point in the execution, we can group the vertices of the graph into "buckets", according to their rank.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] We define the buckets' ranges inductively, as follows: Bucket 0 contains vertices of rank 0.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Bucket 2 contains vertices of ranks 2 and 3.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Then bucket B will have vertices with ranks in the interval $[{\text{tower}}(B-1),{\text{tower}}(B)-1]$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] We can make two observations about the buckets' sizes.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The maximum number of elements in bucket $\left[B,2^{B}-1\right]$ is at most ${\frac {2n}{2^{B}}}$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Since each find operation makes exactly one traversal that leads to a root, we have *T*1 = *O*(*m*).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Also, from the bound above on the number of buckets, we have *T*2 = *O*(*m*log**n*).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] For T3, suppose we are traversing an edge from u to v, where u and v have rank in the bucket [*B*, 2*B* − 1] and v is not the root (at the time of this traversing, otherwise the traversal would be accounted for in T1).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Fix u and consider the sequence $v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{k}$ that take the role of v in different find operations.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Because of path compression and not accounting for the edge to a root, this sequence contains only different nodes and because of Lemma 1 we know that the ranks of the nodes in this sequence are strictly increasing.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The worst-case time of the `Find` operation in trees with **Union by rank** or **Union by weight** is $\Theta (\log n)$ (i.e., it is $O(\log n)$ and this bound is tight).
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Blum gave an implementation of the operations that does not use path compression, but compresses trees during $union$ .
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] His implementation runs in $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ time per operation, and thus in comparison with Galler and Fischer's structure it has a better worst-case time per operation, but inferior amortized time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1999, Alstrup et al. gave a structure that has optimal worst-case time $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ together with inverse-Ackermann amortized time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The regular implementation as disjoint-set forests does not react favorably to the deletion of elements, in the sense that the time for `Find` will not improve as a result of the decrease in the number of elements.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is possible to extend certain disjoint-set forest structures to allow backtracking.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The basic form of backtracking is to allow a `Backtrack(1)` operation, that undoes the last `Union`.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] A more advanced form allows `Backtrack(i)`, which undoes the last i unions.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The following complexity result is known: there is a data structure which supports `Union` and `Find` in $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ time per operation, and `Backtrack` in $O(1)$ time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this result, the freedom of `Union` to choose the representative of the formed set is essential.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Better amortized time cannot be achieved within the class of separable pointer algorithms.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set data structures model the partitioning of a set, for example to keep track of the connected components of an undirected graph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This model can then be used to determine whether two vertices belong to the same component, or whether adding an edge between them would result in a cycle.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The Union–Find algorithm is used in high-performance implementations of unification.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] This data structure is used by the Boost Graph Library to implement its Incremental Connected Components functionality.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is also a key component in implementing Kruskal's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a graph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] The Hoshen-Kopelman algorithm uses a Union-Find.
[src:union-find-algorithm/disjoint-set-data-structure] Union-find can be used to implement reasonably performant Type inference algorithms.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] A minimum spanning tree of a connected weighted graph is a connected subgraph, without cycles, for which the sum of the weights of all the edges in the subgraph is minimal.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] For a disconnected graph, a minimum spanning forest is composed of a minimum spanning tree for each connected component.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] This algorithm was first published by Joseph Kruskal in 1956, and was rediscovered soon afterward by Loberman & Weinberger (1957).
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Other algorithms for this problem include Prim's algorithm, Borůvka's algorithm, and the reverse-delete algorithm.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] At the termination of the algorithm, the forest forms a minimum spanning forest of the graph.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] If the graph is connected, the forest has a single component and forms a minimum spanning tree.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] The following code is implemented with a disjoint-set data structure.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] It represents the forest *F* as a set of undirected edges, and uses the disjoint-set data structure to efficiently determine whether two vertices are part of the same tree.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] For a graph with E edges and V vertices, Kruskal's algorithm can be shown to run in time *O*(*E* log *E*) time, with simple data structures.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] This time bound is often written instead as *O*(*E* log *V*), which is equivalent for graphs with no isolated vertices, because for these graphs *V* / 2 ≤ *E* < *V*2 and the logarithms of V and V2 are again within a constant factor of each other.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] To achieve this bound, first sort the edges by weight using a comparison sort in *O*(*E* log *E*) time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Once sorted, it is possible to loop through the edges in sorted order in constant time per edge.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Next, use a disjoint-set data structure, with a set of vertices for each component, to keep track of which vertices are in which components.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Creating this structure, with a separate set for each vertex, takes V operations and *O*(*V*) time.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] The final iteration through all edges performs two find operations and possibly one union operation per edge.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] These operations take amortized time *O*(*α*(*V*)) time per operation, giving worst-case total time *O*(*E* *α*(*V*)) for this loop, where α is the extremely slowly growing inverse Ackermann function.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] This part of the time bound is much smaller than the time for the sorting step, so the total time for the algorithm can be simplified to the time for the sorting step.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] First, it is proved that the algorithm produces a spanning tree.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Second, it is proved that the constructed spanning tree is of minimal weight.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Let G be a connected, weighted graph and let Y be the subgraph of G produced by the algorithm.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Y cannot have a cycle, as by definition an edge is not added if it results in a cycle.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Y cannot be disconnected, since the first encountered edge that joins two components of Y would have been added by the algorithm.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] We show that the following proposition ***P*** is true by induction: If *F* is the set of edges chosen at any stage of the algorithm, then there is some minimum spanning tree that contains *F* and none of the edges rejected by the algorithm.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Kruskal's algorithm is inherently sequential and hard to parallelize.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] It is, however, possible to perform the initial sorting of the edges in parallel or, alternatively, to use a parallel implementation of a binary heap to extract the minimum-weight edge in every iteration.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] As parallel sorting is possible in time $O(n)$ on $O(\log n)$ processors, the runtime of Kruskal's algorithm can be reduced to *O*(*E* α(*V*)), where α again is the inverse of the single-valued Ackermann function.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] A variant of Kruskal's algorithm, named Filter-Kruskal, has been described by Osipov et al. and is better suited for parallelization.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] The basic idea behind Filter-Kruskal is to partition the edges in a similar way to quicksort and filter out edges that connect vertices of the same tree to reduce the cost of sorting.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] The following pseudocode demonstrates this.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Filter-Kruskal lends itself better to parallelization as sorting, filtering, and partitioning can easily be performed in parallel by distributing the edges between the processors.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Finally, other variants of a parallel implementation of Kruskal's algorithm have been explored.
[src:union-find-algorithm/kruskal-s-algorithm] Examples include a scheme that uses helper threads to remove edges that are definitely not part of the MST in the background, and a variant which runs the sequential algorithm on *p* subgraphs, then merges those subgraphs until only one, the final MST, remains.
